commentBody:
@Steve L

I take it you have a beef with TIP ROAST?

That's really not all that rare.

@Cat Lady Margaret

Reverberant cat bellies -- I'm in awe!





.

@Mark

Nah, you’ve just been spelling it wrong all along.

It’s correct in the puzzle. YAY is for hearing good news.

@Mark

I've been spelling it wrong in my head this whole time too and read the answer like "yeah big," which isn't a thing. 

Lifelong learning!

@Steve L

I am gobsmacked. I'm happy to take your word for it. I had no idea it was spelled YEA, and I was a champion speller in my day. Just never saw it written down. Being informal English, it's not actually something one usually writes down.

I stand corrected, and impressed.

@Isabeau

West of the Mississippi it’s “Carb-loads”
East of the Mississippi it’s CARBOLOAD

@Mike
I think it's time you throw in the tau.

(The emus said theta blocked this if they'd seen it.)

@Mike
Say, do you remember that Fifties hit with "Gamma Lambda ding-dong"??  
I can't get it outta my head....

@Gregg
"OMNI Hotels" by itself isn't a very helpful answer unless you assume I know Wyndham is the name of a hotel. (To me, "Wyndham" is John Wyndham, author).

But with the "hotel" hint, and Google, it turns out that I do know lots of hotels owned by Wyndham. However, I only know them as Super 8, Ramada, Travelodge, Days Inn, etc. I never once noticed the "by Wyndham" tag in those names. But I wouldn't consider the upscale OMNI to be an alternative to any of those!

@Beth
Nope, I haven't changed my mind. 

I didn't need to Google "The stain of sin" to know it was valid, but just because a clue is valid doesn't mean it's a good clue. And while it's only one man's opinion, I still think "Producers of stains" wasn't very good.

@Mick

That is a nice clue, but it’s not particularly original. 

November 30, 2024 (Oliver Goodrige and Juan Gavarito) had [Styles of singing].

@Sam Lyons
Google tells me Bosco would likely be a Karakachan.
Impressive looking beast with quite the reputation!

@Hobby Gardener
Where do you live?  I was near Giessen for a couple of years (Grossen Linden)...  still have friends living near Marburg.  We thought we would travel more after our honeymoon in 1979...but life got in the way.  Now the thought of flying is daunting...
...but I would SO love to have Dallmayr coffee again.

@Mean Old Lady
We live about 25 km north of Hamburg. It’s about 1 1/2 hrs south of the Danish border.
Yes, flying has become daunting. Staying at home and quilting and gardening are much more to my taste these days!

@Dave Munger
The use of ON A PAR has nothing to do with golf, at least not how I've used it. eg equal in importance or quality:
My car is on a par with the other managers'.

@Chris

Your confidence about what "Nobody says" is impressive.
I wonder how you did your research on this.

@The X-Phile

Well, at least Chris simply said that "skinny" for inside info was "mental", not that no one says it.

(We know what "mental" is short for in that case...)

@Dave Munger
We NON-golfers use ON A PAR...
There are other uses for the phrase than references to "a good walk--ruined."

@Chris, I've heard both carb load and carbo load. I've said "on a par with" all my life. 

"What's the skinny" is more than a little familiar to me. 

To be so cranky over sayings YOU don't use lends a level of defensiveness to your post, which I'm pretty sure wasn't your intent. I don't know how old you are, but in these puzzles the slang can run a wide gamut of decades or even centuries. Being in my seventh decade gives me a definite edge sometimes, in terms of exposure, but I'm often challenged/stymied by current slang. I do not assert that those sayings aren't legit simply because I'm unfamiliar with them.

@Chris  Nope, here in the states CARBOLOAD is a thing, particularly in marathon running.   
    Nope, here in the states "what's the skinny?" meaning "what's the inside information?" while not terribly common, is a term.  
     Yup, you're right "ON A PAR" is nonsense, a silly error.  It's "on par".

@Spatial K

And the answer could have been ABC (as in a list)...
Speaking of Spatial...that is my bugaboo...  more than one quilt has a (to me) glaring error where I turned a block the wrong way and couldn't SEE it...  (One quilt went to a show anyway; the judges missed it, too.  Feathered Stars have a lot of points.....

@Bruce

(In a Cuban accent):

Bru-CYYYYYY!!!!

@Mtmetz

Just another example of misuse becoming so common that it finds its way into the dictionary and becomes just an alternate form, even if it doesn’t make sense. 

But that’s just the evolution of language; you don’t have to like everything that comes down the pike.

@Eric Hougland
I’m with you. 
Sorry @Bruce, but as I can’t ‘hear’ the tone of your comment that story sounds like you admire the driver. Which would beggar belief. My sincere apologies if that’s not what you intended.

@Helen Wright

No, I don't admire the driver. I think she bought into an aspect of pop culture that destroyed her life and ended someone else's, and I have some compassion based on that, but I definitely do not admire her.

I think there need to be many speed cameras employed that both clock speeds and get a clear image of the driver. And I think that driving over 100 mph or street racing should bring a ten-year revocation of that person's driver's license and a year in jail. And I think the car should be crushed in front of them

@Bruce
Phew. 
I’ve never seen any of the franchise. Tbh, anything with Vin Diesel in is a turn off for me. But as an old lady I don’t think I’m his/the franchises target audience!

@Vaer
I wanted an UNDERGROUND PATH or a SECRET TUNNEL or a FALSE BOOKCASE....
       ....Adrian?  Please?

@Helen Wright

Our pediatrician expressed amazement that my kids could swallow pills--which I much preferred to liquid medicatiions.
I told him that if your offspring can swallow peas whole, then pills are no challenge...  LOL

@Mean Old Lady
There's a small town near me that has a regular SPEED TRAP for a 25 MPH stretch after a 4-way stop. It must be their only source of revenue. My mom got a ticket there.

As for the "falling apart" mis-clue, I'm reminded of the ending of "Poltergeist," where the house IMPLODES. To accomplish that, the crew attached lots of cables to the interior structure of the house, and hooked the other end to a bulldozer. Happily, the 'dozer was able to pull the whole thing into the basement in one go, and it looked like the house was being sucked into a dimensional portal.

@Dave K.

Think about colors bleeding from one garment to another, not human blood. I got it pretty quickly. 

Read the comments re "on a par," and you'll find plenty of people who use that phrase. Perhaps next time, check the comments before proclaiming no one has ever said a particular thing.

@David Connell

Thanks for expanding my vocabulary nice again. 

You’re absolutely right. I read YEA big and picture someone estimating a size with their hands.

@Hardroch

Yeah, I used to get flipped off by my wife a lot.  Not so much these days.

Maybe she doesn't love me anymore?

@Alex

I just had Lomo saltado last weekend! It was in a Colombian restaurant! So good! I was out of town for that, but there's a wonderful Ecuadorian restaurant near me that serves it. Delicious and an immediate gimme for me in the puzzle. 

Hopefully, one day, I'll make it to Peru... or at least a Peruvian restaurant and try it there. ☺️

Spoilers in this post.
@G
Yeah, I was expecting the constellations' names not what we got.  My surprise was Maiden, not Virgin. Wikipedia agrees, but I guess maybe too much astrology on my part, since I've only ever seen the constellation referred to as the second there.

@Vaer

Re: Not sure if that's the same one.

Yep, same one.  I caught that it was not the names but the "things/entities" but *maiden* did not occur to me at first.

@RJ

Ha! 

A different interpretation I hadn't thought of...

@HeathieJ

I remember when I was a kid I'd glance at the sun.  I don't know what was happening, but it looked to me like the sun was showing cracks, and that it was about to break into pieces.

I was a weird little kid.  And yet I turned out just magnificently.  Go figure.

@Sean

COMMA was a good misdirect! I personally was thinking of dates as the fruit for a while, but movie was a good option. 

If you're interested, there's some discussions in the comments about your two quibbles. I can personally attest to saying both of those answers as is when the occasion arises, so I didn't find them quibbling but YEA instead of Yay surprised me!  ☺️
